Access Control Vulnerability 

Access control is a security mechanism that determines what a user is allowed to do within an application. It ensures that only authorized users can view or interact with specific data and features.

Access control relies on three core concepts:


Identity — who the user is
Roles — the category the user belongs to
Permissions — the actions the user is allowed to perform


When access control fails, users may be able to access data or functionality they should not have permission to use.


The 3 Mechanisms of Access Control

1. Authentication

Verifies the identity of a user, typically through credentials such as a username and password.

2. Session Management

Maintains the state of a logged-in user throughout their activity, ensuring the system continues to recognize them as authenticated.

3. Authorization (Access Control)

Determines what an authenticated user is permitted to do or access within the application.


Broken Access Control

Broken access control occurs when a system fails to properly enforce restrictions on user actions. This flaw can allow users to reach data or features that should be protected or hidden.

Attackers can exploit broken access control to:


View other users' information
Perform administrative actions without proper authorization


Broken access control is considered one of the most common and severe web security vulnerabilities.


Vertical Access Control

Vertical access control refers to a system where different users are granted different levels of permission based on their role.


Higher-level users (e.g., administrators) have broad control over the application.
Lower-level users (e.g., standard users) have limited access to features and data.


This model ensures that sensitive actions can only be performed by users with the appropriate authority.

Example: Only an administrator can delete a user account or modify system settings — a standard user cannot.

