Horizontal Access Control

Horizontal access control refers to a system where users share the same permission level but are restricted to accessing only their own data.

Each user can view or modify only their own resources — not those belonging to other users at the same access level. This ensures privacy between peers and prevents unauthorized access to another user's information.

Example: A bank customer can view only their own account details, not the accounts of other customers.


